Mangrove forests thrive near the mouths of large rivers where 
river deltas provide lots of sediment.
Many lives could have been saved if mangroves and reefs had been conserved in a
healthy state, said the Mangrove Action Program, an environmental organization
based in Port Angeles, Washington.
The Mangrove Action Program estimates that there are 16,000 hectares (40,000
acres) of mangroves left in the world.
